### Description
Changes to support string input.
Multer middleware is being called inside the endpoint function body to handle string input case effectively.
Changes in the utility functions to handle string input.
Added tests for string input.
<!--Include a summary of the change and relevant motivation/context. List any dependencies that are required for this change.-->

Fixes #27 

### Type of Change:
<!--**Delete irrelevant options.**-->

- Code

**Code/Quality Assurance Only**
- This change requires a documentation update (software upgrade on readme file)
- New feature (non-breaking change which adds functionality pre-approved by mentors)



### How Has This Been Tested?
<!--Describe the tests you ran to verify your changes. Provide instructions or GIFs so we can reproduce. List any relevant details for your test.-->
Added tests for string input.

### Checklist:
<!--**Delete irrelevant options.**-->

- [x] My PR follows the style guidelines of this project
- [x] I have performed a self-review of my own code or materials
- [ ] I have made corresponding changes to the documentation
- [x] Any dependent changes have been merged


**Code/Quality Assurance Only**
- [x] My changes generate no new warnings
- [x] I have added tests that prove my fix is effective or that my feature works
- [x] New and existing unit tests pass locally with my changes
- [x] Any dependent changes have been published in downstream modules

### Description

<!--Include a summary of the change and relevant motivation/context. List any dependencies that are required for this change.-->
Initialized express server that will run on port 3001 -> Entrypoint is index.js
![log](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/30899040/121544286-3a904200-ca27-11eb-9d60-e887c0eb62e2.JPG)
Dependencies for the server include eslint, express, mocha.
The react app has been initialized using create-react-app.
Initialized eslint.

Fixes #7 #8 

### Type of Change:
<!--**Delete irrelevant options.**-->

- Code
- Documentation

**Code/Quality Assurance Only**
- This change requires a documentation update (software upgrade on readme file)

[{'comment_id': 648561654, 'comment_body': "I'd personally prefer using words like web for a directory over frontend. 
And maybe server for the backend. It's a little unusual for the naming to include frontend/backend.

For instance - https://github.com/thoughtworks/epirust/tree/master/web in this web directory, we have both the server and client code - it's referred to as server and the frontend is react spa or in your case it could be web. 
If you like look at some good open source project directory structures or web and server also is cool for me.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 9, 18, 23, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 648566870, 'comment_body': 'One .gitignore in the root is easier than having it hidden inside this directory. .gitignore in project root can ignore node_modules for both server(backend) and web(frontend).
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 9, 18, 30, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 648567403, 'comment_body': 'no need for 2 .gitignore mentioning the same thing. Make one additional  .gitignore on the parent level that is common to both so you can put node_modules there instead of duplicating what you want to ignore.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 10, 18, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 649416649, 'comment_body': 'You don't even need a .gitignore here. Make one at parent level and ignore node modules, it will ignore for both the react app and the server. Also, can you test the gitignore? Because this is one repository, I"m not sure if they work at the sub directory level?
Irrespective make one common one at root. You don't need this file for one line', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 10, 18, 13, 56, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 650045148, 'comment_body': 'Got it.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 11, 14, 55, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'pcgamer1', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 650060752, 'comment_body': 'Add when you have tests! Right now we have 0 tests, based on what you have in the future add them on a need basis. In this manner, we might end up adding a lot of stuff we probably might never need.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 11, 15, 15, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 650064561, 'comment_body': 'Have you compared mocha/chai with jest? Why would you prefer them over jest? https://jestjs.io/ check check?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 11, 15, 20, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 650179681, 'comment_body': "Got it, have read about both of them now and I remember using Jest for endpoint testing. Jest is preferable for small-medium scale projects as we don't have to setup other libraries to work with it while mocha is suitable for more advanced use-cases as it has more features and dependencies. Jest should be fine for us and I'll add it later when I'm writing tests.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 11, 18, 10, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'pcgamer1', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 650870398, 'comment_body': '

", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 14, 11, 41, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 650873375, 'comment_body': "Henceforth, for any spike (research), when you do search and learn things eg. why jest over chai or chai over jest, also share resources that you're referring to. ### Description

<!--Include a summary of the change and relevant motivation/context. List any dependencies that are required for this change.-->
Initialized express server that will run on port 3001 -> Entrypoint is index.js
![log](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/30899040/121544286-3a904200-ca27-11eb-9d60-e887c0eb62e2.JPG)
Dependencies for the server include eslint, express, mocha.
The react app has been initialized using create-react-app.
Initialized eslint.

Fixes #7 #8 

### Type of Change:
<!--**Delete irrelevant options.**-->

- Code
- Documentation

**Code/Quality Assurance Only**
- This change requires a documentation update (software upgrade on readme file)


### Checklist:
<!--**Delete irrelevant options.**-->

- [x] My PR follows the style guidelines of this project
- [x] I have performed a self-review of my own code or materials
- [x] I have commented my code or provided relevant documentation, particularly in hard-to-understand areas
- [x] I have made corresponding changes to the documentation
- [x] Any dependent changes have been merged


**Code/Quality Assurance Only**
- [x] My changes generate no new warnings
- [x] Any dependent changes have been published in downstream modules

[{'comment_id': 648561654, 'comment_body': "I'd personally prefer using words like web for a directory over frontend. 
And maybe server for the backend. It's a little unusual for the naming to include frontend/backend.

For instance - https://github.com/thoughtworks/epirust/tree/master/web in this web directory, we have both the server and client code - it's referred to as server and the frontend is react spa or in your case it could be web. 
If you like look at some good open source project directory structures or web and server also is cool for me.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 9, 18, 23, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 648566870, 'comment_body': 'One .gitignore in the root is easier than having it hidden inside this directory. .gitignore in project root can ignore node_modules for both server(backend) and web(frontend).
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 9, 18, 30, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 648567403, 'comment_body': 'no need for 2 .gitignore mentioning the same thing. Make one in the parent directory', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 9, 18, 31, 10, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 648616543, 'comment_body': 'Renamed backend to server and frontend to react-app.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 9, 19, 32, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'pcgamer1', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 649415451, 'comment_body': '@pcgamer1 I still see two .gitignores which can stay but they have repeated stuff, eg. node_modules. Make one additional  .gitignore on the parent level that is common to both so you can put node_modules there instead of duplicating what you want to ignore.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 10, 18, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 649416649, 'comment_body': 'You don't even need a .gitignore here. Make one at parent level and ignore node modules, it will ignore for both the react app and the server. Also, can you test the gitignore? Because this is one repository, I"m not sure if they work at the sub directory level?
Irrespective make one common one at root. You don't need this file for one line', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 10, 18, 13, 56, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 650045148, 'comment_body': 'Got it.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 11, 14, 55, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'pcgamer1', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 650060752, 'comment_body': 'Add when you have tests! Right now we have 0 tests, based on what you have in the future add them on a need basis. In this manner, we might end up adding a lot of stuff we probably might never need.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 11, 15, 15, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 650064561, 'comment_body': 'Have you compared mocha/chai with jest? Why would you prefer them over jest? https://jestjs.io/ check check?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 11, 15, 20, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 650179681, 'comment_body': "Got it, have read about both of them now and I remember using Jest for endpoint testing. Jest is preferable for small-medium scale projects as we don't have to setup other libraries to work with it while mocha is suitable for more advanced use-cases as it has more features and dependencies. Jest should be fine for us and I'll add it later when I'm writing tests.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 11, 18, 10, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'pcgamer1', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 650870398, 'comment_body': '
Can you add a line about what this project is and why are we doing it? @pcgamer1 ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 14, 11, 38, 40, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 650872164, 'comment_body': "Also, for now, it's okay for the README to be so bland, but as we progress, please continue to update it with better instructions and possibly a better format, please. Not on priority as of now
Refer: 
https://github.com/othneildrew/Best-README-Template or any other template for that matter. ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 14, 11, 41, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 650873375, 'comment_body': "Henceforth, for any spike (research), when you do search and learn things eg. why jest over chai or chai over jest, also share resources that you're referring to. There are a lot of blogs/resources which can push us either way, it's important to know and understand how and where you drive conclusions from.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 14, 11, 43, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'meenakshi-dhanani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 651962585, 'comment_body': "@meenakshi-dhanani @AbhiramH I've added a template based on the above suggestion.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 15, 16, 33, 38, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'pcgamer1', 'type': 'User'}]
